STEP 4: SMART Questions

4.1: Is there a statistically significant difference in the Response variable (Proposal Accepted vs Rejected) based on the Income of the individual?

# Filtering the required data
proposal_df$IncomeCategory <- cut(proposal_df$Income, breaks = c(5000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000), labels = c("Low Income", "Medium Income", "High Income", "Very High Income"), include.lowest = TRUE)

# bar chart
ggplot(proposal_df, aes(x = IncomeCategory, fill = factor(Response))) + geom_bar(position = "dodge") + labs(title = "Proposal Acceptance by Income Category", x = "Income Category", y = "Count", fill = "Proposal Response") + theme_minimal()

Null Hypothesis: There is no statistically significant difference in the Proposal Response based on an Individual’s Income. Alternative Hypothesis: There is a statistically significant difference in the Proposal Response based on an Individual’s Income.

# Contingency table for Income Category and Proposal Response
contingency_table <- table(proposal_df$IncomeCategory, proposal_df$Response)

# Chi-Square Test
chi_square_test <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
chi_square_test
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  contingency_table
## X-squared = 1, df = 3, p-value = 0.8

The P-value is greater than significance level(0.05). Therefore, we cannot reject the Null Hypothesis. There is no statistically significant difference in the Proposal Response based on an Individual’s Income.

4.3: Which classification model (logistic regression, decision tree, or random forest) is the most suitable for predicting whether a proposal will be accepted or rejected based on RomanticGestureScore, CompatibilityScore, and DistanceKM?

Logistic Regression Model

# Load required libraries

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets (Assuming proposal_df is your data)
set.seed(123)  
index <- createDataPartition(proposal_df$Response, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- proposal_df[index, ]
test_data <- proposal_df[-index, ]

# Logistic Regression Model
logistic_model <- glm(Response ~ RomanticGestureScore + CompatibilityScore + DistanceKM, data = train_data, family = binomial)

# Predictions on test data
logistic_probabilities <- predict(logistic_model, test_data, type = "response")
logistic_predicted <- ifelse(logistic_probabilities > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Convert predictions and actuals to factors
actual <- as.factor(test_data$Response)
predicted <- as.factor(logistic_predicted)

# Confusion Matrix
confusion <- confusionMatrix(predicted, actual, positive = "1")

# Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score
accuracy <- confusion$overall["Accuracy"]
precision <- confusion$byClass["Pos Pred Value"]  # Precision
recall <- confusion$byClass["Sensitivity"]       # Recall
f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

# AUC
roc_curve <- roc(actual, logistic_probabilities, levels = c("0", "1"))
auc_value <- auc(roc_curve)

# Print metrics
cat("Logistic Regression Performance Metrics:\n")
## Logistic Regression Performance Metrics:
cat("Accuracy: ", accuracy, "\n")
## Accuracy:  0.798
cat("Precision: ", precision, "\n")
## Precision:  0.835
cat("Recall: ", recall, "\n")
## Recall:  0.919
cat("F1-Score: ", f1_score, "\n")
## F1-Score:  0.875
cat("AUC: ", auc_value, "\n")
## AUC:  0.815
# Plot ROC Curve with AUC value
plot(roc_curve, main = "ROC Curve for Logistic Regression", col = "blue", lwd = 2)
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "gray", lty = 2)

# Add AUC value to the plot
auc_text <- paste("AUC =", round(auc_value, 3))
text(0.6, 0.2, auc_text, col = "blue", cex = 1.2)

#### Desicion Tree Model

# Load required libraries


# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(proposal_df$Response, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
trainData <- proposal_df[trainIndex, ]
testData <- proposal_df[-trainIndex, ]

# Decision Tree Model
decision_tree_model <- rpart(Response ~ RomanticGestureScore + CompatibilityScore + DistanceKM, 
                             data = trainData, method = "class")

# Visualize the Decision Tree
rpart.plot(decision_tree_model, type = 2, extra = 104, main = "Decision Tree")

# Predictions
predicted_probabilities_tree <- predict(decision_tree_model, proposal_df, type = "prob")[, 2]  # Probabilities for class 1
predicted_classes_tree <- predict(decision_tree_model, proposal_df, type = "class")            # Predicted classes

# Convert actual values to factor
actual <- as.factor(proposal_df$Response)

# Confusion Matrix
confusion_tree <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(predicted_classes_tree), actual, positive = "1")

# Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score
accuracy_tree <- confusion_tree$overall["Accuracy"]
precision_tree <- confusion_tree$byClass["Pos Pred Value"]  # Precision
recall_tree <- confusion_tree$byClass["Sensitivity"]        # Recall
f1_score_tree <- 2 * (precision_tree * recall_tree) / (precision_tree + recall_tree)

# AUC and ROC Curve
roc_curve_tree <- roc(actual, predicted_probabilities_tree, levels = c("0", "1"))
auc_value_tree <- auc(roc_curve_tree)

# Print Metrics
cat("Decision Tree Metrics:\n")
## Decision Tree Metrics:
cat("Accuracy:", round(accuracy_tree, 3), "\n")
## Accuracy: 0.788

## Precision: 0.816
cat("Recall:", round(recall_tree, 3), "\n")
## Recall: 0.937
cat("F1-Score:", round(f1_score_tree, 3), "\n")
## F1-Score: 0.872

4.4: How can we improve the accuracy of the Random Forest model predicting proposal acceptance by adding Income, Age, and DistanceKM as features? Which additional features could further enhance the model’s performance, and how would the model accuracy change?
